The economic feasibility study from 2001 was based on the assumption that the section near the border and the section leading through the Bohemian Uplands would be concealed at the same time.
At the time of the test, it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian Uplands would not be opened on the original date.
This reduces the aforementioned EIRR values.
The costs of both sections as at 31.12.2005 amounted to € 897 million excluding VAT. and thus 27.4% higher than in the economic outlook 2001 basis.
In addition, there is a risk that section 0805 will take on a different and more complex course, which would affect the profitability of the project.
The economic feasibility study showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway with a daily traffic volume of at least 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010 is economically justified. The forecast for 2008 had predicted 22,940 vehicles per day.
However, a study on detour routes as an alternative to the missing section through the Bohemian Uplands assumes traffic volumes of 12 600 to 13 750 vehicles per day in 2007. The project is then below the profitability limit.
Increased traffic on routes designed to replace the missing section of the Central Bohemian Region is likely to result in congestion and thus increased external costs, which were not taken into account in the initial performance study.
The aforementioned reduction in revenue and cost increases means that the already low EIRR will not be reached for the construction of the D 8 bordering the border.
The construction of the border near section of the D 8 is therefore uneconomical.
Also during the construction of the A 17 there were cost increases as in the construction of the two above-mentioned sections of the D 8.
As part of the macroeconomic assessment for the Federal Transport Infrastructure Plan 1992, the federal ministry responsible for transport went from investment costs of approx. € 320 million.
Thus, it determined a benefit / cost ratio of 4.6.
Meanwhile, the costs have rd. € 670 million and reduced the benefit / cost ratio by more than half.
The BRH had independently of the parallel tests with the NKÚ in the years 2003 to 2005, the cost of planning and construction of the A 17 motorway tested.
He noted that the authority responsible for the approval required a non-essential landscape tunnel for the third section of the A 17.
In the course of the audit, the BRH managed to convince the Federal Ministry and the Road Administration of the overflow of the landscape tunnel.
This allowed € 10 million in construction costs and € 150,000 in annual operating costs to be avoided.
During the examination of the first section of the A 17, the BRH found that the construction work was insufficiently prepared.
The following example makes this clear:
In the planning phase, the road administration waived a condition assessment of the rock on the surface of the Dölzschener wall, as this was difficult to access.
Only when the tunneling tunnel reached the wall did she catch up.
It showed that the rock was more weathered than assumed in the call for tenders.
Elaborate measures such as anchorages, injections and rockfall protection nets for around € 3.3 million have become necessary.
The road construction administration not only bore the costs for additional, anyway required services, such as the securing of the Dölzschener Wand, but also for those which would not have been necessary in the case of a proper construction preparation.
These include expenses as a result of disrupted construction processes (€ 3.2 million), additional training of the excavation crew (€ 0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the extension of the construction period (€ 7 million).
This additional expenditure of around € 10.7 million is not offset by any lasting added value.
The BRH took this and other measures as an opportunity to call on the Federal Ministry to better take charge of the technical supervision it is responsible for major road construction measures.
In this context, it should be urged that road authorities introduce quality assurance systems.
Benefits of cooperation for BRH and NKÚ The cooperation fulfilled the expectations of both courts of auditors.
The BRH received information on the planning, the awarding of the contract and the construction of the border bridge.
Both audit offices developed bridge and tunnel pricing data that will be useful in future audits.
The NKÚ determined that the most important structural parameters for the bridges, tunnels and carriageway of the D 8 are not different from those of the A 17.
The co-investigators of both SAIs gathered valuable experience that will be useful in future audits.
